//  First Aid
        "first aid intro" => "First aid is the first and immediate assistance given to any person suffering from either a minor or serious illness or injury, with care provided to preserve life, prevent the condition from worsening, or to promote recovery. It includes initial intervention in a serious condition prior to professional medical help being available, such as performing cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR) while waiting for an ambulance, as well as the complete treatment of minor conditions, such as applying a plaster to a cut. \n\nMental health first aid is an extension of the concept of first aid to cover mental health, while psychological first aid is used as early treatment of people who are at risk for developing PTSD.",
        "sections" => "Sections",
        "section a" => "A. The four basic steps of First Aid",
        "section b" => "B. Musculoskeletal injuries",
        "section c" => "C. Burns",
        "section d" => "D. Poisonous bites and allergies",
        "section e" => "E. Choking hazards and drowning",
        "section f" => "F. Heart attack and stroke",
        "section a1" => "1. Take safety measures",
        "sec a1 text" => "Ensure that there will be no further danger and that there is no chance for you to become a victim as well. Try and think if there is something in your surroundings that could endanger you. Take safety measures such as calling the fire or police departments. If the victim needs to be moved, do so <strong>after</strong> you take the necessary safety measures for both of you.",
        "section a2" => "2. Seek help",
        "sec a2 text" => "If you are alone, raise your hands and shout <strong>&quotHelp!&quot</strong> so that passersby and people around you might notice you. Ask them for their help, whether it is to call an ambulance, holding people off from getting too close to the victim or assisting with applying first aid.",
        "section a3" => "3. Assess the situation",
        "sec a3 text" => "Before proceeding to the application of first aid, first assess the situation. One easy approach to do so is the following:\n\n<strong>A</strong>irway : open and check the passability of the airway\n\n<strong>B</strong>reathing: check their breathing\n\n<strong>C</strong>irculation: check their pulse and look for any signs of bleeding\n\n<strong>D</strong>isability: check for physical or mental disability\n\n<strong>E</strong>xposure: further evaluation of the person's state\n\nThey might also show some symptoms that could be of help, like pain, difficulty in breathing, tendency to faint, etc. Finally, check your surroundings for clues.",
        "section a4" => "4. Call an ambulance",
        "sec a4 text" => "There's only so much you can do without any medical knowledge. If you are alone, make sure to keep the person in need safe and contact a hospital	so they can get medical attention as soon as possible. The phone call must be short and clear. Tell them your name, what happened, how many people are in need of help and your current location. Remember to stay calm.",
        "sec b text" => "In case of a <strong>fracture</strong> apply ice wrapped in some kind of cloth for about 10-15 minutes. The ice will relieve the pain, but make sure not to apply the ice  directly to the person's skin due to risk of an ice burn. \n\nIn case of a <strong>wound</strong> make sure the injury doesn't come in contact with anything due to risk of infection. Wear gloves for both of your safety and pour water until the injury is clean. Dry the wound with sterilized medical cloth and wrap around it or in case of smaller wounds apply bandaids. \n\nIn case of a <strong>bone fracture</strong> immobilize the fractured body part completely. Then call an ambulance to move the person to the hospital. Until then make sure to help them stay calm and apply ice.",
        "sec c text" => "Immediately cool the burned area with cool tap water (10-25 degrees Celcius) until the pain goes away. This will temper the heat in the burned area and reduce the damage done to the tissue. <strong>Warning!</strong> It is <strong>prohibited</strong> to apply ice or ice-cold water due to high risk of hypothermia.",
        "sec d text" => "In case of a <strong>bee/wasp sting</strong> remove the stinger immediately with a flat object (like a coin or a card). Wash the sting with water and soap. Remove any jewelery and apply cool patches of cloth. Rub the sting with antihistamine ointment.\n\n In case of an <strong>allergy</strong> wash the affected body part with water and soap. Relieve the rash with a mix of water and vinegar with an analogy of two parts water and one part vinegar. Consult a doctor in case of need for further medication and try to figure out what caused the allergy to avoid said cause in the future.",
        "sec e text" => "In case of <strong>partial obstruction</strong> where the person can cough with no difficulty urge them to keep coughing, stay on stand-by and observe if the object is removed or not. \n\nIn case of <strong>total obstruction</strong>, lean them forward and deliver 5 strong hits on the back. If not successful, perform 5 abdominal thrusts with one hand cleched like a fist between the person's chest and stomach. If the above proved to be unsuccessful still, swap between the two methods until the object is removed or the person has lost consciousness. In that case call an ambulance immediately and proceed to perform cardioplumenary resuscitation (CPR) by applying force to their chest area. \n\n\nIn case of <strong>drowning</strong> make sure to never approach the victim. In most cases people who approach a drowning person end up drowning themeselves. The correct course of action is keeping your distance and finding an object you could use to throw and pull them to safety. If the person gets out of the water and is unconcious perform cardioplumenary resuscitation (CPR) by applying force to their chest area immediately. If the person recovers their senses, find something to keep them warm with and make sure to see them taken to the hospital, even if they seem to be fine.",
        "sec f text" => "In case of a <strong>heart attack</strong> and the person is still conscious, have them sit down and loosen any tight clothes that may make it difficult for them to breath. If it's the first time happening, call an ambulance. Help them take any medicine that were given to them by the doctor. If the symptoms persist, make sure the person is taken to a hospital. \n\nIn case of <strong>heart failure</strong> call an ambulance and lie the person down to a solid surface. Immediately begin performing cardioplumenary resuscitation (CPR) and keep doing so until medical assistance arrives. \n\nIn case of a <strong>stroke</strong> call an ambulance and put 2-3 pillows below the person's head and back. Loosen any tight clothes and don't give them anything to drink or eat. Cover them with a blanket. If they lose consciousness check their breathing. If they are breathing, lift them up in a sitting position.",
        "first aid important" => "<strong>Important!</strong>\n\n Here you can find every emergency number in any country around the world.",
        "emergency numbers" => "Worldwide emergency phone numbers",
